oninkrijk","Ayr, Ayrshire, Scotland":"Ayr, Ayrshire, Schotland","Barns of Ayr":"Ayrshire, Schotland"},"en":{"1295–":"1295–Deceased","1280–1340":"1280–1340","1290–1330":"1290–1330","1295–Female":"1295–Deceased","1290–1370":"1290–1370","1335–Male":"1335–Deceased","1339–Male":"1339–Deceased","1260–1346":"1260–1346","1261–1312":"1261–1312","1330":"1330","1340":"1340","1295":"1295","1261":"1261","1260":"1260","1370":"1370","1280":"1280","1290":"1290","1335":"1335","1346":"1346","1312":"1312","about 1339":"about 1339","about 1335":"about 1335","1339":"1339","Ayrshire, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Ayrshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","Rowallan Castle, Craigie, Ayrshire, Scotland":"Craigie, Ayrshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","Kilmarnock, Ayrshire, Scotland":"Kilmarnock, Ayrshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","Ayr, Ayrshire, Scotland":"Ayr, Ayrshire, Scotland","Barns of Ayr":"Ayrshire, Scotland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Mure","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Italian (Sicily): variant of   Morea  .","Scottish: variant of   Muir  .","English: occupational name from Old French <i>muer</i> ‘mewer’, i.e. someone who tended to hawks in the cages in which they were kept while moulting. Compare   Mew  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Mura","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Japanese Akio, Hideo, Masao, Nanako, Tsutomu, Yoshi.  French Alphonse, Amie, Henri.","German: altered form of some similar (like-sounding) German or perhaps French surname. It is also common in France (Alsace), where it was first recorded in the form <i>Morrau</i>, later <i>Murra(w)</i>.","Italian (southern Sardinia): topographic name or nickname from Sardinian <i>mura</i> ‘mulberry’ or ‘blackberry’."]},{"name":"Muir","meanings":["Scottish: topographic name for someone who lived on a moor, from Older Scots <i>muir</i> ‘moor’ (an expanse of bare, wild upland country). There has been some confusion with   Mure  ."]},{"name":"Morea","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Angelo, Saverio, Domenic, Ferdinando, Rocco.  Spanish Manuel, Carlos, Cesar, Elvira, Jesus, Mauricio.","Italian (Apulia): from the personal name <i>Morea</i>, originally a habitational name from Morea, the medieval name of the Greek region of Peloponnese, named as the land of mulberry trees, from <i>mōrea</i> ‘mulberry’.","Spanish and Catalan: habitational name from any of the places called Morea, in Badajoz, Navarre, and Lleida provinces."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Margaret Mure was born in 1295, in Kilmarnock, Ayrshire, Scotland, United Kingdom, her father, Sir William Mure 3rd of Rowallan, Knight, was 36 and her mother, Margaret Lindsey, was 34. She married Sir Roger De Blare of that Ilk, 5th Lord of Blair in 1335, in Ayrshire, Scotland, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 2 sons."},"et":{"1295–":"1295–Surnud","1280–1340":"1280–1340","1290–1330":"1290–1330","1295–Female":"1295–Surnud","1290–1370":"1290–1370","1335–Male":"1335–Surnud","1339–Male":"1339–Surnud","1260–1346":"1260–1346","1261–1312":"1261–1312","1330":"1330","1340":"1340","1295":"1295","1261":"1261","1260":"1260","1370":"1370","1280":"1280","1290":"1290","1335":"1335","1346":"1346","1312":"1312","about 1339":"umbes 1339","about 1335":"umbes 1335","1339":"1339","Ayrshire, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Ayrshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Rowallan Castle, Craigie, Ayrshire, Scotland":"Craigie, Ayrshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Kilmarnock, Ayrshire, Scotland":"Kilmarnock, Ayrshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Ayr, Ayrshire, Scotland":"Ayr, Ayrshire, Scotland","Barns of Ayr":"Ayrshire, Scotland"},"fi":{"1295–":"1295–Kuollut","1280–1340":"1280–1340